(I) 1. (in nanoseconds)
Insertion:
pushAtFront: 1894 pushAtBack: 5270083 insertAt middle of list: 2528320
Removal:
popFromFront: 3534 popFromBack: 4730469 removeAt middle of list: 2239455
Access:
first: 400 last: 5153235 elementAt for middle of list: 2216651
operations ranked: Removal, Access, Insertion
2. Operations that accessed elements closer to the front of the list were
faster because of the way that the elements in the linked list are accessed.
In each LinkedList, there is a pointer to the front, allowing for easy access
when performing functions on it. However, for the other elements at further
indices, the program must first recurse to the element before the function 
can be done. 
3. Access is slower in linked lists, while on average, insertion and removal 
take around the same amount of time. Linked lists are generally faster than
array lists when accessing the first element because of the easier access. 
However, because of indices, arraylists are typically faster in accessing 
later elements in the lists. 
Qyuestions:
Q1: I found it easier to implement the functions that accessed the first 
element in linked lists because of the front pointer in the linked lists. 
Additionally, after I completed creating the ElementAt helper function, 
creating the rest of the functions became much easier because I could reuse
the helper function. 
Q2: The functions that accessed a specific index was harder to implement
because I would have to recurse to each index instead of calling it normally.
Q3: The client would only have to change teh constructor type because both
lists use the same functions and should contain the same output.